{{Infobox person | name = Ronald Corey | image = <!-- just the filename, without the File: or Image: prefix or enclosing [[brackets]] --> | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1938|12|13|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = | awards = [[Order of Canada]] }} '''Ronald Corey''', {{Post-nominals|country=CAN|CM}} (born 13 December 1938)<ref>{{cite book|title=Canadian Who's Who, 1992|author=Kieran Simpson}}</ref> is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] businessman and former professional [[ice hockey]] executive with the [[Montreal Canadiens]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL). In 1991, he was made a Member of the [[Order of Canada]].
==Businessman== As of 2012, Corey serves as director of Transamerica Life Companies, Schiff Nutrition International Inc. and The Canadian Museum for Human Rights. He is also president of Ronald Corey Groupe Conseil Ltée.<ref name="bb">{{cite web |url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=8092915&ticker=LB:CN&previousCapId=4494416&previousTitle=B2B%20Trust |title=Executive Profile: Ronald Corey, O.C. |publisher=[[Bloomberg Businessweek]] |accessdate=July 19, 2010}} </ref> Corey has also served as Chairman of the Port of Montreal.<ref name="bb"/> Prior to joining the Canadiens' organization, Corey was president of the Carling-O'Keefe brewery.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Globe and Mail |title=The Board of Directors of La Brasserie O'Keefe Limitee is pleased to announce the appointments of Mr. I. L. Matte as Chairman of the Board and Mr. Ronald Corey as President of the Company. |date=September 3, 1980 |page=B3}} </ref>
==Montreal Canadiens executive== On November 12, 1982, Corey was appointed [[president]] of the Canadiens.<ref>{{cite news |work=The Globe and Mail |title=ROUNDUP Hockey |page=S7 |date=November 13, 1982}}</ref> During his term as president, the team won two [[Stanley Cup]]s; in [[1985–86 NHL season|1986]] and [[1992–93 NHL season|1993]]. Corey was president for the building of the [[Bell Centre]], however during the 1990s, the team's business declined under the indirect ownership of parent company [[Molson Brewery]] by [[Foster's Group|Foster's]].<ref name="gaz-1999">{{cite news |work=Montreal Gazette |last=Todd |first=Jack |date=September 3, 1999 |title=New hope for Habs fans; Team president, Molson CEO sound serious about future they're serious |page=F1}}</ref>
Corey was known for his good treatment of past Canadiens' stars [[Maurice Richard]] and [[Guy Lafleur]]. In 1986, he also brought [[Doug Harvey (ice hockey)|Doug Harvey]] back into the Canadiens' organization, as a scout and arranging the retirement of his jersey number 2.<ref>{{cite news |work=Ottawa Citizen |title=Doug Harvey; The roller coaster life of a hockey legend |date=January 11, 1986 |last=McAuley |first=Lynn |page=E1}}</ref> He was also criticized by the media for poor management decisions in the hiring of Montreal Canadiens general managers. One famous action of Corey's was the firing, four games into the 1995–96 season, of the entire Canadiens' hockey management - general manager [[Serge Savard]] and coaches [[Jacques Demers]], [[Carol Vadnais]] and [[Andre Boudrias]], and replaced them with [[Rejean Houle]] and [[Mario Tremblay]]. Houle had no previous general manager experience while Tremblay had no coaching experience, and the moves would indirectly lead to the departure of star goaltender [[Patrick Roy]] weeks later. Earlier, however, Savard had been hired by Corey with no prior front-office experience and went on to put together 2 Stanley Cup-winning teams.<ref>{{cite news |work=Montreal Gazette |last=Todd |first=Jack |title=Corey hurt by his love for Habs |date=June 1, 1999 |page=E1}}</ref> Corey retired in May 1999, after Molson openly discussed selling the team, he was unwilling and unable to fulfill that mandate, and Molson went on installing new team president Pierre Boivin. The Canadiens were soon sold to American businessman [[George Gillett (American businessman)|George Gillett]].
